## Step 2 — The Copy-Paste Prompt (run this in Copilot Chat)

Once the instruction file is in place, open **Copilot Chat** in VS Code and paste this:

```
@workspace

Please generate a full Repository and Solution Overview for the **[APPLICATION NAME] ([GEAR ID])** application based on the current workspace.

Follow the output structure defined in `.github/copilot-instructions.md`.

The overview will be used in a ServiceNow Knowledge Article, so use professional headings and clear plain English throughout.

Make sure you cover:
- The Visual Studio solution name and all projects within it
- The purpose of each project (DB, SSIS, SSRS, SSAS, Data Lake, etc.)
- The top-level folder structure of the repo
- The overall data flow from source to reporting
- Any notable dependencies or integrations visible in the repo
```

For Talisman, replace the placeholder with:
> `[APPLICATION NAME]` → `Talisman`
> `[GEAR ID]` → `7337`

For MDM next time:
> `[APPLICATION NAME]` → `MDM`
> `[GEAR ID]` → `7317`

---

## Why This Approach Works

| Factor | Why it's right |
|---|---|
| `@workspace` | Forces Copilot to scan the **actual repo files**, not hallucinate |
| Instruction file | Ensures consistent output structure across all repos |
| Parameterised prompt | One prompt, swap the name/ID per project |
| ServiceNow-ready format | Headings + bullets paste cleanly without reformatting |

---

**One honest caveat:** Copilot's `@workspace` quality depends on how well the repo is indexed. If the solution is very large, it may miss some deeper nested projects. In that case, you can **add specific files as context** by dragging them into the Copilot Chat panel before running the prompt (e.g. the `.sln` file, key `.sqlproj` files). That guarantees those are included.

